Abstract
This paper presents a cycle-accurate simulation of the ST-T1024 (DLM) standard, modeled against the Qualcomm Snapdragon 8 Gen 4 architecture specification. Because ST-T1024 is deterministic by construction, its performance can be derived exactly from stated hardware specifications — cycle counts, power rail characteristics, and memory latencies — without requiring physical hardware access. This paper presents that derivation, states clearly where it stands (simulated, not yet hardware-validated), and requests a joint benchmark with Qualcomm AI Research to close that gap.
Based on this simulation, ST-T1024 projects:
~97.8% simulated energy reduction vs. standard transformer inference
≤680 ns simulated worst-case execution time (WCET), against an 800 ns architectural target
99.9% simulated power gating efficiency (0V idle state)
1/N scaling of energy per active tile (N = number of domain tiles)
All figures below are simulation outputs, derived from the stated hardware specification in Section 2, not physical hardware measurements. Section 8 states the current implementation status and the specific ask to Qualcomm AI Research to close the gap between simulation and silicon.
