Introduction
1.1 The Energy Wall Problem
Current transformer-based LLMs face a structural constraint: inference cost scales with model size regardless of query complexity. A question about gravity consumes the same compute as a query about quantum field theory. At cloud scale, this translates to hundreds of megawatts of avoidable waste.
The industry response — larger models, faster interconnects, more chips — compounds the problem rather than resolving it. The architectural assumption is the issue, not the engineering execution.
1.2 The ST-T1024 Solution
The ST-T1024 standard (also known as DLM — Deterministic Language Model) proposes a paradigm shift:
Feature
Implementation
Domain Tiling
Query space partitioned into N independent tiles. Only relevant tile activates.
Ternary Logic
Weights encoded as {-1, 0, +1}. No multipliers required.
FSM Orchestration
Hard real-time scheduling with WCET ≤ 800 ns (architectural target).
FIS Triage
Fuzzy inference routes queries before tile execution.
Power Gating
Inactive tiles drop to 0V immediately after execution.
1.3 Why This Simulation Is Different From a Typical Benchmark
Because ST-T1024 is deterministic by construction, its behavior can be computed exactly from a stated hardware specification, rather than measured statistically across many runs. This simulation is:
Reproducible — no statistical variance in the model itself
Transparent — every cycle count and its derivation is shown
Hardware-agnostic in its method — maps to any bitwise-capable processor
Open — full implementation in the companion repository
Explicit about status — simulated, pending hardware validation (Section 8)
